article.description: Sheryl Swoopes tied a season high with 27 points as the Houston Comets defeated the Utah Starzz 73-57 Friday night for their sixth straight victory.
article.headline: Streaking Comets end Starzz's four-game streak
article.linkText: Comets win sixth straight behind Swoopes' season-high 27 points
article.story:
HOUSTON (AP) -- Sheryl Swoopes tied a season high with 27 points
as the Houston Comets defeated the Utah Starzz 73-57 Friday night
for their sixth straight victory.

	   The loss snapped Utah's four-game winning streak.

Swoopes shot 10-for-19. Seventeen of her points came in the
first half.

"I think we've finally realized how good we can be,'' Swoopes
said. "Utah is a very good team and we knew what we had to do to
beat them. They are a very tough team to rebound against and defend
and I think we did that.''

	   Marie Ferdinand led the Starzz (8-4) with 16 points. Margo Dydek
pulled down a game-high 16 rebounds but made just two of her 10
shots.

	   Natalie Williams made a layup with 13:04 left in the game to tie
the score at 45, but Houston (11-3) responded with a 16-2 run.

	   Swoopes scored five points during the run and Tina Thompson and
Janeth Arcain added four each to give the Comets a 61-47 lead with
6:19 to go.

	   Houston jumped out to a 23-15 lead in the first 9:26 of the game
before Utah battled back and scored nine straight points to take a
24-23 lead with 6:06 left.

	   Ferdinand scored five points during the run to give Utah its
second lead of the night, but Houston responded with a run of its
own, outscoring the Starzz 12-5 in the final five minutes to take a
35-29 lead into halftime.

	   Utah coach Candi Harvey said that better decisions should have
been made to keep Houston in check.

	   "We just didn't make the right pass, the smart pass,'' Harvey
said. "Tonight we were trying to make the difficult play and
against that type of athleticism, you just can't do that. This is a
team we can beat, a team that we should be able to compete with.''

	   "I thought once again our defense was really good and I am
really pleased tonight with how we defensed Utah,'' Houston coach
Van Chancellor said. "We played a little zone, and I think that
was the best we've played the zone all year. That was just a good
win for us.''
